  "M": "Let T be a time series of patent counts, T = {t1, t2, ..., tn}, where ti is the count of patents in year i. A recurring structural behavior is defined as a significant change in the growth rate of patents, which can be identified by a change in the trend of the time series. This change can be quantified by the first derivative of the time series, D(T) = {d1, d2, ..., dn-1}, where di = ti+1 - ti. A significant change in the growth rate is indicated by a change in the sign of di or a substantial difference in the magnitude of di compared to previous values.",
  "T": "The structural behavior involves a temporal analysis of patent counts over time, focusing on changes in growth rates. The behavior is comparable across different categories of patents (e.g., GANs, diffusion models, GenAI modes) and countries. The aggregation level is annual patent counts. The boundary condition is the availability of a time series of patent counts with sufficient data points to identify trends and changes in growth rates."
}

{
  "T_hat": "A comparative growth pattern exists between entities ei and ej in set E for attribute m over interval [t_start, t_end] if CAGR(ei, m; t_start, t_end) - CAGR(ej, m; t_start, t_end) > epsilon, where epsilon >= 0. Entity ei is a growth leader if its CAGR is the maximum in E. All entities must have non-zero, non-missing starting values for m."
}

